{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564362"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:12:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:12:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16972"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16972"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.41,0.03,0.43,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9662"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68088"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9662"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16972"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4470"},{"type":"tags","id":"4671"},{"type":"tags","id":"11153"},{"type":"tags","id":"11993"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68088"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her first pregnancy booking visit at 12 weeks gestation. She is a refugee from Somalia who arrived in Australia two years ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination with consent and a female interpreter present, the external genitalia shows removal of the clitoral hood and partial removal of the clitoral glans. The labia minora and majora are intact, and the vaginal opening is normal in size without scarring.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this type of female genital mutilation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 3","Type 2","Type 4","Type 1","Type 5"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with evidence of female genital mutilation (FGM), which is classified by the World Health Organization into four main types based on the extent of tissue removal and anatomical changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1\u003C/strong\u003E FGM, which this patient has, involves partial or total removal of the clitoral glans and/or prepuce (clitoral hood). The key feature distinguishing Type 1 is that only the clitoral region is affected, with preservation of the labia and normal vaginal opening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2\u003C/strong\u003E FGM involves partial or total removal of the clitoral glans and labia minora, with or without excision of the labia majora. This patient\u0027s labia are intact, ruling out Type 2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 3\u003C/strong\u003E FGM, also known as infibulation, involves narrowing of the vaginal opening through creation of a covering seal by cutting and repositioning the labia minora or majora. This patient\u0027s vaginal opening is normal in size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 4\u003C/strong\u003E FGM includes all other harmful procedures to female genitalia for non-medical purposes, such as pricking, piercing, incising, scraping, and cauterization. The findings in this case clearly fit Type 1 criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 5\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised classification of FGM according to the World Health Organization system, which only includes Types 1-4.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecognition of FGM type is important for appropriate antenatal care planning, as different types may require different approaches to delivery. Women with Type 3 FGM often require deinfibulation, while those with Type 1 may deliver vaginally without specific intervention.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Female genital mutilation is classified into four types by the World Health Organization based on the extent of tissue removal and anatomical changes.","Type 1 FGM involves partial or total removal of the clitoral glans and/or prepuce.","Antenatal assessment of women with FGM is essential for planning appropriate care during pregnancy and childbirth."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Female genital mutilation (FGM) [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Female-Genital-Mutilation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16972"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T09:41:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T09:42:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9662"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68088"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0